===Glyph origin===
{{Han etym}}
{{Han compound|門|虫|ls=psc|c1=p|c2=s|t2=snake}}. The {{zh-l|*虫}} radical was a common component of the names of barbarians ({{zh-ref|Schuessler, 2007}}), probably reflecting the Min people's worship of snakes ({{zh-ref|Li, 2017}}).

===Etymology===
{{zh-ref|Matisoff (2003)}} relates it to {{inh|zh|sit-pro|*s-b/m-ruːl||snake}}, but this comparison is no longer held in STEDT.

In most modern Min varieties and some other non-Mandarin varieties of Chinese, including Hakka and Xiang, it is read with a level tone ({{zh-l|*平聲}}), which is the expected reflex based on rime dictionaries. In Mandarin and the remaining non-Mandarin varieties, it is read with a rising tone ({{zh-l|*上聲}}), probably due to analogy with the phonetic component of {{ltc-l|閔}} ({{zh-ref|Li, 2017}}).

